artilage is one of the few immune-privileged tissues in the body in that it is essentially avascular and therefore not subjected to close β€�internalβ€� immunological surveillance [59]. n incomplete central tolerance is most likely the dominant component of this special immune condition, a tolerance that can be breached when transgenes are expressed in cartilage and the cartilage-specific overexpression is β€�leaky,β€� especially in the embryo. everal lines of evidence support this hypothesis. or example, cartilage link protein [60] or otherwise arthritogenic human 1 domain (unpublished data) expression in mice, driven by the rat type  collagen promoter and enhancer, may be detected in cartilage tissue, but the transcript and protein could also be detected in other embryonic tissues. dditionally, when cartilage  (or ) is degraded by various matrix metalloproteinases, the newly generated neoepitopes may provoke an autoimmune reaction [61]. urther evidence is provided by posttranslational events (e.g., citrullination), as molecules unrelated to cartilage (e.g., filaggrin [62β€“64]) are first citrullinated far before the onset of joint inflammation. ubsequently, additional molecules (e.g., fibrinogen, vimentin, type  collagen,  aggrecan, ±-enolase, and a few virus proteins) also undergo posttranslational modifications (citrullination), and the cumulative effect of (auto)immune reactions may breach the immune tolerance in genetically susceptible human individuals.
 lthough immunity to the cartilage  aggrecan has been less extensively studied than immunity to type  collagen (), cartilage  is also considered to be a causal factor in rheumatoid joint diseases [65β€“67]. ither humoral or cellular immunity, or both, to human cartilage s have been detected in patients with  [65β€“79], and the two most recent studies reported that the citrullinated version of a dominant arthritogenic (5/48) peptide of human cartilage  [80, 81] induced substantial cytokine (-17, -22, -6, ±, ³) production by  cells from the majority of  patients [78, 79].  cells from the same  patients responded poorly to the native (noncitrullinated) peptide in both studies, and  cells from healthy subjects did not respond [78] or responded only to the citrullinated peptide by producing -6 [79]. lthough the majority of  patients tested were positive for anti-citrullinated cyclic peptide (anti-) antibodies (), -cell response to the citrullinated  peptide was also noted in some  patients [78, 79].4. Tissue-Restricted (Cartilage) Antigens Can Provoke Arthritis in Genetically Susceptible Mice and May Contribute to the Severity of RA
Cartilage is one of the few immune-privileged tissues in the body in that it is essentially avascular and therefore not subjected to close β€�internalβ€� immunological surveillance [59]. An incomplete central tolerance is most likely the dominant component of this special immune condition, a tolerance that can be breached when transgenes are expressed in cartilage and the cartilage-specific overexpression is β€�leaky,β€� especially in the embryo. Several lines of evidence support this hypothesis. For example, cartilage link protein [60] or otherwise arthritogenic human G1 domain (unpublished data) expression in mice, driven by the rat type II collagen promoter and enhancer, may be detected in cartilage tissue, but the transcript and protein could also be detected in other embryonic tissues. Additionally, when cartilage PG (or CII) is degraded by various matrix metalloproteinases, the newly generated neoepitopes may provoke an autoimmune reaction [61]. Further evidence is provided by posttranslational events (e.g., citrullination), as molecules unrelated to cartilage (e.g., filaggrin [62β€“64]) are first citrullinated far before the onset of joint inflammation. Subsequently, additional molecules (e.g., fibrinogen, vimentin, type II collagen, PG aggrecan, Ξ±-enolase, and a few virus proteins) also undergo posttranslational modifications (citrullination), and the cumulative effect of (auto)immune reactions may breach the immune tolerance in genetically susceptible human individuals.
 Although immunity to the cartilage PG aggrecan has been less extensively studied than immunity to type II collagen (CII), cartilage PG is also considered to be a causal factor in rheumatoid joint diseases [65β€“67]. Either humoral or cellular immunity, or both, to human cartilage PGs have been detected in patients with RA [65β€“79], and the two most recent studies reported that the citrullinated version of a dominant arthritogenic (5/4E8) peptide of human cartilage PG [80, 81] induced substantial cytokine (IL-17, IL-22, IL-6, TNFΞ±, IFNΞ³) production by T cells from the majority of RA patients [78, 79]. T cells from the same RA patients responded poorly to the native (noncitrullinated) peptide in both studies, and T cells from healthy subjects did not respond [78] or responded only to the citrullinated peptide by producing IL-6 [79]. Although the majority of RA patients tested were positive for anti-citrullinated cyclic peptide (anti-CCP) antibodies (ACPA), T-cell response to the citrullinated PG peptide was also noted in some ACPA patients [78, 79].
