<sections.6>
7. verall ummary and erspectives
verall, mouse studies, especially with congenic strains, appear to be a fundamental resource for the identification of candidate gene(s) in . uring the past 15 years or so, almost concurrent with the first human genomic studies in , a number of rodent (mouse and rat)  studies have been performed. t approximately the same time, both the human and mouse genome sequencing studies were completed and, simultaneously, unlimited numbers of new markers became available for both species. he number of human studies expanded; tens of thousands of  patients, along with controls, were genotyped; new and more reliable  arrays became available; more risk alleles became identified in  and in almost all autoimmune diseases. owever, after extensive progress in , the direction of  research moved towards confirmatory studies of previously tested patients, examinations of different ethnic groups or comparisons of the therapeutic effects of different biologics. riefly, human studies turned to mainly in silico and meta-analysis studies rather than aimed towards finding causative and functional (aetiological) reasons. he previously identified genomic regions were confirmed using a high marker density, but the large chromosome regions with tens of bps in size still remained unmanageable. nly a very few s causing missense mutations proved to be associated with disease, and usually only in a narrow selection of the patient population. owever, the number of risk alleles increased, and previously identified marker positions were confirmed.
nfortunately, animal studies also slowed down, although due to completely different reasons from human studies. ncreasing the number of new combinations of disease-susceptible and disease-resistant inbred strains revealed more and more s, but not a disease-causing gene. ecognising the limitations as well as the potential of both human and mouse , approximately 10 years ago, a number of congenic strains carrying the most promising traits representing the strongest clinical phenotypes were established. hese strains carry overlapping traits identified in different animal models and syntenic with genomic regions identified as  risk alleles. n other words, at the time when the human  explored the most critical  risk alleles, congenic backcrossing had selected inbred  strains with syntenic regions to the major human risk alleles. e selected two s for more detailed analysis: gia26/ia5/m. Cia21/Eae3 on mChr3 and rat Cia10, corresponding to the PTPN22/CD2 allele on human Chr1 (Figure 2); Pgia2/Cia2/Cia3 on mChr2 (corresponding to the TRAF1/C5 allele on hChr9). Then, we generated IVSC strains (Figures 1 and 2, Pgia26 is shown). All other congenic and subcongenic strains were cryopreserved. The two major/dominant mouse QTLs were separated into narrow subtraits and simultaneously tested for arthritis susceptibility, for disease onset and severity, and for over 15 biomarkers that might have some potential relevance for RA [84]. Simultaneously, some of the IVSC genomic regions representing homogeneous regions of disease-susceptible and disease-resistant IVSC mice (and the corresponding parent genomic regions) were sequenced, and a few mutated genes were identified (with β€�knownβ€� or completely unknown function). Occasionally, these genes had not been previously associated with arthritis, but all of them had localised in close proximity to a gene used to name the human RA risk alleles. The analyses of these genes and a targeted selection of appropriate human genomic DNA samples used for high-throughput sequencing are currently in progress in a number of laboratories. The approaches and concepts outlined in this paper (especially in Sections 4 and 5) are not the only possible avenues for the identification of the RA (or other autoimmune disease)-related defects in the genome. However, these approaches may allow us to merge currently available results of human GWAS with findings of GWAS and IVSC studies in mice. Nonetheless, to confirm the role of these genes in RA, researchers must identify not only the genomic identity but also the corresponding functional defects in mice analogous with those present in patients with RA. Unfortunately, mechanistic and functional studies, manipulation of the genome, and pretesting of new therapeutic approaches cannot be applied in human patients, which underlines the relevance of and necessity for laborious genetic studies in animal models.
